    <a href="/reading/number-theory/" class="text-sm mb-4 inline-block">&larr; back to Number Theory</a>

    <h1>Primitive Roots</h1>
    <p class="text-gray-400 text-sm mb-6">Jim Hefferon &middot; Elementary Number Theory &middot; <a href="https://jheffero.w3.uvm.edu/numbertheory/">Ch. 7</a></p>

    <div class="bg-zinc-800 rounded-lg p-5 mb-8 callout">
      <p class="text-lg" style="max-width:none">A <strong>primitive root</strong> mod p is a number whose powers cycle through all nonzero residues. Every prime has one. Finding discrete logarithms (inverting this cycle) is believed to be hard, which is the foundation of Diffie-Hellman key exchange.</p>
    </div>

    <!-- SVG: Powers of generator cycling through residues -->
    <h3>Order of an element</h3>
    <p>The order of a mod n is the smallest positive integer k such that a^k &#x2261; 1 (mod n). A primitive root mod p has order p - 1: its powers hit every nonzero residue exactly once.</p>

    <div class="flex justify-center my-6">
